    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:ba2a6797-c26e-41fc-babc-e3b1671c87a3",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 56-year-old man who appears mildly overweight, with a sedentary but not frail presentation. He is neatly dressed, wears bifocals, and often rubs his eyes after reading or using a computer for long periods. He reports several months of increased thirst, needing to urinate more often during the day and once or twice overnight, and more fatigue than usual by late afternoon. He has not had dramatic weight loss, chest pain, or acute illness, but has noticed that minor cuts on his hands seem to take longer to heal than they used to.\n\nHe works full-time as an accounts manager for a regional building supply company, a job that involves long desk hours, frequent driving between branch offices, and irregular lunch breaks. His meals are often convenient rather than planned: breakfast may be skipped, lunch is commonly fast food, and dinner is usually large and eaten late. He drinks several cups of sweetened coffee daily and usually has 1-2 beers on weekends. He does not smoke and quit social smoking in his twenties.\n\nOutside of work, {patientName} enjoys watching football, doing occasional yard work, and meeting friends for weekend barbecues. He intends to exercise more but has struggled to maintain a routine because of work stress and chronic poor sleep. He is married, lives with his spouse, and has two adult children who live independently. His wife has encouraged him to seek care because of his fatigue and frequent urination.\n\nSocially, {patientName} is engaged and functional, but he has become more self-conscious about his weight and energy level over the past few years. He describes himself as \"generally healthy\" and has not always attended regular preventive visits. He is concerned about developing the same \"sugar problems\" that affected other family members and is motivated, though somewhat anxious, to make lifestyle changes now that he has been diagnosed."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:6883aa6c-fbc8-4f40-9cad-14c8bf0a6d0c",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a history of obesity and borderline hypertension noted during prior workplace health screenings, but he has not consistently followed with a primary care clinician. He also has dyslipidemia previously identified on routine labs, though he has not been taking medication reliably. There is no known history of coronary artery disease, stroke, chronic kidney disease, diabetic eye disease, foot ulcers, or peripheral neuropathy.\n\nHe was not previously hospitalized for diabetes-related problems and has never experienced diabetic ketoacidosis or severe hypoglycemia. Past acute care visits have been limited to minor musculoskeletal strain and an episode of uncomplicated diverticulitis several years ago managed without surgery. He denies current tobacco use and reports light alcohol intake, mainly on weekends. His diet is high in refined carbohydrates and portion sizes are often large, and his physical activity is limited to intermittent walking and yard work.\n\n{patientName} sleeps poorly, snores according to his spouse, and often feels unrefreshed in the morning, raising concern for possible obstructive sleep apnea. He reports increased thirst and urinary frequency over the past several months, along with reduced exercise tolerance related more to fatigue than dyspnea. He has no history of pancreatitis, chronic liver disease, or long-term glucocorticoid use."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
